[3]
Date: Sun 8 May 2022
Source: Daily Mail [edited]
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-10793627/Faulty-air-conditioner-killed-three-Americans-luxury-Bahamas-resort-Sandals-guests-say.html


A 65-year-old Florida man killed by a suspected air conditioning leak at a luxury Sandals resort was there to celebrate his wedding anniversary with his wife. [He] died Friday morning [6 May 2022] at Sandals Emerald Bay in Exuma while on vacation with his wife, 64, [who] woke up to find herself paralyzed and her late husband not moving, the couple's devastated son told ABC News.

Another man and woman -- both from America -- also died but have yet to be named. All victims are said to have suffered convulsions before their deaths.

The stricken son said his mom had first fallen ill on Thursday [5 May 2022] and visited a local clinic. She was discharged shortly afterward and believed her health had improved. [She] is now being airlifted back to Florida for further medical treatment.

Meanwhile, another vacationer has shared dramatic testimony of what happened. [....] "It sounds like it may have been a fault with the a/c in the unit, causing a toxic coolant leak," the post reads. Most air conditioners use a chemical called freon as a coolant, a moderately toxic gas that is tasteless and mostly odorless, and that can prove deadly if inhaled over a prolonged period of time.

[The other vacationer's] claims come as police continue to investigate the deaths of the 3 American guests, 2 of whom complained of illness to hotel staff the previous evening. An investigation by police discerned that those 2 guests, a couple staying at the same villa, suffered convulsions before their death. 'Our initial investigations revealed that the couple found in the second villa complained of illness the previous evening,' a statement released by New Providence police said. 'They attended the local medical facility and, on completion of receiving treatment, they returned to their lodging.'

Hotel staff came across the 1st body shortly after 9 a.m. Friday [6 May 2022] in a villa separate from that of the now-deceased couple, police said in their statement. Officers at the George Town Police Station arrived on the scene shortly thereafter, where they were notified by hotel staff that another 2 guests -- the couple -- had also been found unresponsive in another villa. Police entered the 1st villa to find [a hotel guest] lying on the ground with no signs of trauma, authorities said. The local doctor pronounced [the guest] dead at the scene. [The guest's] wife was then airlifted to a hospital in the capital city Nassau Friday morning [6 May 2022], Exuma MP and Minister of Tourism Chester Cooper said. She has since been airlifted to Kendall Regional facility in Florida, her son, who learned of his parents' deaths after receiving a call from the US Embassy Friday [6 May 2022] night, told ABC.

After speaking to his mother, [the son] detailed to the outlet how she had found her husband Friday [6 May 2022] morning unresponsive on the floor, after also falling ill the previous [day]. "She woke up, and my dad was laying there on the floor, and she couldn't move," he said. "Her legs and arms were swollen and she couldn't move and she screamed to get someone to come in the door." She told her son she had fallen ill on Thursday [5 May 2022] but 'thought she was alright' after visiting the clinic, he said.

In the 2nd villa, an unidentified man was found 'slumped against a wall in a bathroom' and the woman on a bed, the Royal Bahamas Police Force said in a statement. 'Both individuals showed signs of convulsion,' police said.

They added that no signs of trauma were found on either bodies.

[Byline: Alex Hammer]

